    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:e991235c-9fb9-44f6-a88b-fc102fae9beb",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an 8-year-old girl who appears tired and mildly uncomfortable, sitting close to her mother and speaking in a quieter-than-usual voice because of throat pain. She has a flushed face, enlarged erythematous tonsils with patchy white exudate, tender swollen anterior cervical glands, and intermittent fever. Swallowing is painful, so she has been taking small sips of water and refusing some solid foods over the past two days. Her breath has a mildly foul odor, she occasionally winces when asked to open her mouth wide, and her mother notes she has complained of headache and mild stomachache along with the sore throat.\n\nShe is otherwise a normally active third-grade student who enjoys drawing, playground games, reading beginner chapter books, and weekly dance class. She lives with her parents and a younger brother in a suburban home, attends school regularly, and recently had several classmates out sick with sore throats and colds. During dance and school she shares water bottles less than she should despite reminders, and she often spends time in crowded indoor settings during after-school activities, which increases exposure to common respiratory infections. Her mother reports that {patientName} is usually energetic, sociable, and talkative, making her recent fatigue and decreased appetite especially noticeable.\n\nAt home, {patientName} has a structured routine with school during the day and dance class once weekly. She does not have exposure to tobacco smoke inside the home, though the family has a cat. She has a history of seasonal allergic rhinitis with chronic nasal congestion during spring, and her parents say she often breathes through her mouth and snores lightly when congested. Her diet is generally balanced, but during this illness she prefers cold liquids, yogurt, and soft foods because of odynophagia. Sleep has been somewhat disrupted by throat discomfort, fever, and mouth dryness overnight.\n\nHer parents are attentive and brought her for evaluation after 48 hours of worsening sore throat, fever, swollen neck glands, and visible tonsillar swelling. They mention she has had a few milder sore-throat episodes in prior school years, including one treated supportively at home last winter, but this episode is more painful than usual. On observation she looks mildly ill but not toxic, is breathing comfortably, and remains interactive when encouraged. She is anxious about throat examination but cooperative with reassurance from staff and family."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:1bbe77d2-87d3-40a7-9280-663382354070",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has been generally healthy with normal growth and development and is up to date on routine childhood immunizations. She has seasonal allergic rhinitis with recurrent spring nasal congestion and mouth breathing, but no chronic cardiopulmonary or endocrine disease. Her parent reports one prior urgent care visit for viral upper respiratory infection about a year ago, with no hospitalizations.\n\nSymptoms began approximately two days ago with sore throat and fatigue, followed by fever, reduced appetite, and pain with swallowing. There has been no drooling, stridor, respiratory distress, or neck stiffness. She has had mild headache, abdominal discomfort, and tender swollen glands in the neck. Oral intake is reduced but she is still drinking small amounts. There is recent exposure to school-aged peers with upper respiratory illnesses, and she attends crowded classrooms and after-school dance activities.\n\nHer parents report two prior milder sore-throat illnesses over the last two school years, both self-limited and managed at home without confirmed streptococcal testing; one episode was associated with enlarged tonsils and missed school days. Family members note that she tends to develop throat irritation after periods of heavy nasal congestion because she sleeps with her mouth open. Her younger brother has also had recurrent tonsillitis-type sore throats during early childhood, and her mother recalls frequent throat infections when she was younger.\n\n{patientName} has no known medication allergies. She takes cetirizine during allergy season and a daily pediatric multivitamin. At baseline she is physically active, participates in school and dance, and lives in a stable home environment with good family support. There is no tobacco, alcohol, or drug exposure. She sometimes shares drinks with friends at school or dance and is inconsistent with hand hygiene before snacks, which may increase exposure to common infectious causes of tonsillitis."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
